    {
      "question": "If the polynomial $p(x) = x^4 - 6x^3 + 16x^2 - 25x + 10$ is divided by $g(x) = x^2 - 2x + k$, the remainder is found to be $x + a$. What is the value of $k$?",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Perform long division of $p(x)$ by $g(x)$.",
          "The first term of the quotient is $x^2$. Multiplying $x^2(x^2 - 2x + k)$ gives $x^4 - 2x^3 + kx^2$.",
          "Subtracting from $p(x)$ yields $-4x^3 + (16-k)x^2 - 25x$.",
          "The next term is $-4x$. Multiplying $-4x(x^2 - 2x + k)$ gives $-4x^3 + 8x^2 - 4kx$.",
          "Subtracting yields $(8-k)x^2 + (4k-25)x + 10$.",
          "The next term is $(8-k)$. Multiplying $(8-k)(x^2 - 2x + k)$ gives $(8-k)x^2 - 2(8-k)x + k(8-k)$.",
          "Equate the remainder term of $x$ to $1$ and the constant term to $a$ to solve for $k$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$p(x) = (x^2 - 2x + k)(x^2 - 4x + 8 - k) + (4k - 25 + 16 - 2k)x + (10 - k(8 - k)) \\\\ (4k - 9)x + (10 - 8k + k^2) = x + a \\\\ 4k - 9 = 1 \\\\ 4k = 10 \\\\ k = 2.5$"
      },
