    {
      "question": "If $g(x)$ is the divisor of $p(x) = 2x^4 - 3x^3 - 3x^2 + 6x - 2$ and the quotient $q(x) = 2x^2 - 3x + 1$ with $r(x) = 0$, what is the divisor $g(x)$?",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "options": [
        "(A) $x^2 + 2$",
        "(B) $x^2 + 1$",
        "(C) $x^2 - 2$",
        "(D) $2x^2 - 1$"
      ],
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the division algorithm: $p(x) = g(x)q(x) + r(x)$.",
          "Since $r(x) = 0$, $g(x) = p(x) / q(x)$.",
          "Perform polynomial division of $2x^4 - 3x^3 - 3x^2 + 6x - 2$ by $2x^2 - 3x + 1$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$(2x^4 - 3x^3 - 3x^2 + 6x - 2) \\div (2x^2 - 3x + 1) = x^2 - 2$"
      },
      "topic": "Polynomials",
