    {
      "question": "For a polynomial $p(x)$, if $p(x) = (x^2 - 4)q(x) + (2x + 1)$, what is the remainder when $p(x)$ is divided by $(x - 2)$?",
      "answer": "(B)",
      "options": [
        "(A) $2$",
        "(B) $5$",
        "(C) $0$",
        "(D) $4$"
      ],
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "By the Remainder Theorem, the remainder when $p(x)$ is divided by $(x - a)$ is $p(a)$.",
          "Here $a = 2$.",
          "Substitute $x = 2$ into the expression $p(x) = (x^2 - 4)q(x) + (2x + 1)$.",
          "$p(2) = (2^2 - 4)q(2) + (2(2) + 1) = 0 \times q(2) + 5 = 5$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$p(2) = (4 - 4)q(2) + 4 + 1 = 5$"
      },
